    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>You might also want to consider the Android specific <a href=\"http://developer.android.com/reference/android/text/TextUtils.html#split%28java.lang.String,%20java.lang.String%29\">TextUtils.split()</a> method.</p>\n\n<p>The difference between TextUtils.split() and String.split() is documented with TextUtils.split():</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>String.split() returns [''] when the string to be split is empty. This returns []. This does not remove any empty strings from the result.</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>I find this a more natural behavior. In essence TextUtils.split() is just a thin wrapper for String.split(), dealing specifically with the empty-string case. <a href=\"http://grepcode.com/file/repository.grepcode.com/java/ext/com.google.android/android/5.L_preview/android/text/TextUtils.java#TextUtils.split%28java.lang.String%2Cjava.util.regex.Pattern%29\">The code for the method</a> is actually quite simple.</p>\n"
